Ledit is a very small line editor, keeping a history of previously entered lines
and providing hooks for custom word completion and word skipping (stopping at
 some specific separators). It also provides a minimum support for copy and
paste.

Browsing line history is done with UP and DOWN arrows, the last entered line
being the first accessible by pressing UP arrow. Line history is reordered
when an existing line is reused without any change in order to keep most
recently used lines close together without repeating the same lines. History
can be limited to a maximum number of lines (oldest line in history is dropped
if a new line must be added), or unlimited.

When a line was created or modified, it is temporarily saved if the history is
browsed, in order to allow checking a previous command or copying an argument
in a previous command and resuming editing the first line.

Key mapping:

 UP-ARROW           previously entered line in history
 DOWN-ARROW         next entered line in history

 PAGE-UP            jump to the least recently used line in history
 PAGE-DOWN          jump to the most recently used line in history

 LEFT-ARROW         previous character in current line
 RIGHT-ARROW        next character in current line
 HOME               first character in current line
 END                after last character in current line

 SHFT-LEFT-ARROW    select previous character in current line
 SHFT-RIGHT-ARROW   select next character in current line

 CTL-LEFT-ARROW     hop to the previous separator
 CTL-RIGHT-ARROW    hop to the next separator

 INSERT             toggle insert mode to overwrite mode

 DELETE             delete character under cursor

 BACKSPACE          delete previous character

 TAB                invoke word completion at the cursor position

 CTL-C              copy selected text to clipboard
 CTL-V              paste clipboard to cursor location

 CTL-E              erase characters from cursor to end of line
 CTL-Q              empty line and quit
